8. Filii familiarum] Catilina’s adherents were mostly young men. Cicero calls them, libidinosa et delicata juventus (ad Aa. i. 19); sanguinaria juventus (ad Ate. ii. 7). Comp. in Catil. ii. 3. hos quos volitare in foro, quos stare ad curiam, quos etiam in senatum venire, qui nitent unguentis, qui fulgent purpura. Of the proscriptions of the second triumvirate Velleius remarks: Id tamen notandum, fuisse in proscriptos uxorum fidem summam, libertorum mediam, servorum aliquam, filiorum nullam. ii. 67. Appiam, however, affirms that many Roman matrons helped Catiline with money in the hope that he would exterminate thcir husbands. Bell. Civ. ii. 2.
